TVS iQube.text:
Finding a TVS service center for electric vehicles and getting timely servicing is a significant challenge.

I own the TVS iQube 2.2 kW variant and faced multiple issues shortly after purchase. Within a couple of months, the accelerator sensor needed replacement. A month later, the entire wiring harness had to be replaced due to an error that restricted the vehicle‚Äôs speed to 25 km/h.

The service center took nearly a month to resolve these issues due to the unavailability of spare parts, causing significant inconvenience.

Additionally, the plastic fenders covering the rear wheel on both sides are poorly designed. They come loose easily and produce a rattling noise whenever the scooter hits a pothole.

Most importantly, the subsidy amount promised by TVS, which was supposed to be credited to the buyer‚Äôs account within 30 days of purchase, has not been reflected in my account even after nine months.

TVS is misleading customers with false promises and poor after-sales service. I urge you to create a video highlighting these issues, exposing how companies like TVS use unethical practices to deceive buyers and trap them with substandard products and support.

TVS iQube.text:
TVS iQube is the worst  vehicle choice I have ever made.

Bought in Aug 2023 and currently 33000 kms in odometer. At around 29000 kms they changed the chassis, even though I didn't feel any fault. At around 31000 kms, hub motor failed and replaced. At around 32000, one battery pack changed among two. And now at 33000 kms, still battery not fully charging means, other battery has ro be changed. Also honking is not audible and it's like scooter is crying.

Now all these changes happened under warranty. But all these changes took a week to a month of time in service center. But imagine, an EV sccoter running with all chassis, battery and motor replaced. Only thing left from what I have actually bought is just the screen and outer plastic body. 

And I am already prepared to go through the horrible experience I will have once the warranty gets over. I requested TVS an extended warranty option and they straight away given a NO. Don't wish to sell it as it will be like cheating someone.

My sincere recommendation to everyone is never buy TVS EV products. Once they sell it to you, they don't care about you.

TVS iQube.text:
Very nice video clearing all the deliberate confusion created by TVS. 

I recently bought an ola s1x 4kwh variant at 1.05 lakhs on an offer. Just done 300km so far in 20 days. I did 2 long round trips of 63 and 65km each at speeds of 35 to 42 but mostly 35kmph on cruise  and used up 34% and 35% of charge respectively. That's 1.85 km per 1% of charge. So that's 65km for 35% charge and should easily amount to 150km in 90% leaving you 10% charge spare to cover for anxieties. all this with normal mode and not eco. So ola's claim of 162km on eco mode is not fake at all, its achievable. Of course, my only skill was to never touch the brakes, judge distance beforehand and adjust throttle or use manual regen braking. Im very happy with the results. My weight is 73 and can say 75kg with my clothes and half helmet. Centre stand and mats could add another kg to the kerb weight in total.

TVS iQube.text: I think that scooter he reviewed was from generation 1 or 2, I guess. Newer models having ability to tighten rear brake as per requirement. Actually there is difference between hardness of front brake pads and rear brake shoes, so deterioration occurs easily in rear brake shoes easily than brake pads. Hence company provided option for tightening of rear brake in later versions. It's a combo brakes system and if rider applies only rear brake both brakes got engaged but proportion of rear brake is on higher side and so the wear is. In previous versions there was throttle cable. He is right that TVS assures more safety but as per them this is family scooter and if there is kid on the front area  there are chances of scooter getting accidentally accelerated by kid. The reason why there is throttle + brake option in both iqube and new Jupiter 110 too.

the following serious issues are recurring and making me a number of visits to dealer and a multiple emails for the same.

Ather.text:
Bhavish Aggarwal  announced a Republic Day offer for the Ola S1 Pro at an ex-showroom price of Rs 129,990, and within three days, he reduced it by Rs 15,000. Imagine the plight of those who bought it on Republic Day!
He immediately launched the 3rd Gen vehicles. I paid Rs 8,625 as a down payment for the 2nd gen vehicle, but they are not allowing me to upgrade to the 3rd gen vehicle or apply the reduced price to my purchase. They are asking me to pay the higher amount that was initially announced! Their money is valuable, but ours is not! Don't support such a person.
The Ola app shows one delivery date, but after paying the money, they keep extending it. When asked at the showroom, they give vague answers. This person who makes so many false promises talks about rules. All those rules are designed to benefit him. Where is customer satisfaction?
